    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/07-inference-serving/02-continuous-batching.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Decode is memory-bound, so weights are streamed once per step regardless of batch size B; adding a request is nearly free in memory traffic, which is the entire economic case for batching.; Throughput rises with B as B/(tau0 + beta*B) and flattens toward the compute roofline 1/beta; the scheduler's whole job is to keep B pinned high on the flat part instead of starved at low B.; Static/dynamic (request-level) batching freezes membership for the whole generation, leaking throughput to tail idling and latency to head-of-line blocking at admission.; Continuous batching = iteration-level scheduling: re-derive the running set every forward pass, retiring finished requests and backfilling waiting ones immediately, pinning B near its memory-limited max.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  contbatch-scheduler-state-machine, continuous-batching\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
