    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/09-rag-retrieval/03-rag-architectures.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Parametric memory has hard walls (staleness, finite capacity, no attribution); RAG swaps 'answer from memory' for 'answer conditioned on freshly retrieved docs': P(y|q) becomes P(y|q, D_q), and updating knowledge means re-indexing, not re-training.; RAG is a five-stage pipeline split across time: OFFLINE chunk to embed to index builds the store once/on-update; ONLINE retrieve (optionally rerank) to generate runs per query against that store.; Retrieval and reranking are two DIFFERENT models: a bi-encoder embeds query and document independently (fast, vectors precomputed offline, coarse) to cast a wide net; a cross-encoder scores query+document jointly (slow, per-pair, fine-grained) to precisely re-order the shortlist.; Naive RAG fails in two arenas: RETRIEVAL failures (semantic/keyword mismatch, bad chunk boundaries, top-k missing multi-hop evidence, stale index) and CONTEXT-UTILIZATION failures (lost-in-the-middle, hallucination despite context, redundant near-duplicate chunks).\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  rag-arch-pipeline-five-stages, rag-pipeline\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
