    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/04-kernels-efficiency/09-compilers-fusion.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Eager PyTorch pays a hidden tax on every op: Python/dispatch overhead, a CPU kernel-launch call, and a DRAM round-trip for each intermediate \u2014 even when the arithmetic is trivial.; Kernel fusion keeps intermediates on-chip (registers/shared memory) so a chain of elementwise ops reads inputs once and writes the output once, cutting DRAM traffic ~N->1.; CUDA graphs attack a DIFFERENT bottleneck than fusion: for many small kernels the CPU cannot issue cudaLaunchKernel fast enough, so the GPU sits idle; recording the launch sequence once and replaying it with a single CPU call fills the GPU back-to-back.; torch.compile is a three-stage pipeline: TorchDynamo captures an FX graph from Python bytecode, AOTAutograd traces the joint forward+backward graph, TorchInductor lowers to fused Triton/C++.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  torchcompile-three-layer-stack\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
