    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/05-posttraining-alignment/09-rlvr-reasoning.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: A verifiable reward is a deterministic PROGRAM V(q,o)->{0,1}, not a learned network: it IS ground truth for 'got it right', so there is no approximation error to exploit and you can optimize against it arbitrarily hard.; R1-Zero emergence: because longer reasoning correlates with reaching the right answer on hard problems, the group-relative gradient up-weights 'spend more tokens checking/backtracking/verifying' \u2014 long CoT and the 'aha moment' are DISCOVERED as the cheapest path to correctness, not demonstrated.; The non-negotiable precondition is a mixed-outcome group: a GRPO group needs BOTH wins and losses. If pass@G ~ 0 (too hard) or ~ 1 (too easy) the reward variance is zero, every advantage is zero, and no gradient flows \u2014 the 'dead group'. Emergence only turns in the difficulty sweet spot, hence curriculum.; Verifiers must PARSE -> NORMALIZE -> COMPARE for equivalence, never raw string-match (1/2 = 0.5 = 0.50); a weak verifier's false-negatives poison training by punishing correct answers.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  rlvr-length-emergence-loop\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
